00:43:31,708 --> 00:43:32,541
I have

503
00:43:33,666 --> 00:43:35,125
those who love me

504
00:43:35,208 --> 00:43:36,875
and those who I love.

505
00:43:36,958 --> 00:43:40,958
And anyone who's heard
my bits about my dad should know

506
00:43:41,458 --> 00:43:43,208
just how annoying my dad was.

507
00:43:43,833 --> 00:43:47,250
It's not just his lame jokes, gosh.

508
00:43:47,333 --> 00:43:51,083
Have you ever met a dad
who only cooked instant noodles?

509
00:43:55,958 --> 00:43:57,375
- Hey.
- Dad.

510
00:43:57,875 --> 00:43:59,833
Hey, Le-le, have some noodles.

511
00:44:00,625 --> 00:44:01,583
Have some noodles.

512
00:44:01,666 --> 00:44:03,041
- No, I gotta go.
- Come on.

513
00:44:03,125 --> 00:44:04,000
I'm running late.

514
00:44:04,083 --> 00:44:04,916
Have…

515
00:44:10,708 --> 00:44:12,416
<i>Hello, Le-le?</i>

516
00:44:13,333 --> 00:44:15,083
Okay, you're busy?

517
00:44:15,583 --> 00:44:17,625
Then go do your thing. It's okay.

518
00:44:17,708 --> 00:44:19,583
Okay. Bye-bye.

519
00:44:24,041 --> 00:44:27,750
<i>He was always biking everywhere.</i>

520
00:44:27,833 --> 00:44:30,250
<i>Always out and about.</i>

521
00:44:30,750 --> 00:44:33,916
<i>What's more, he believed in aliens.</i>

522
00:44:38,083 --> 00:44:42,291
<i>My dad used to say if the sky falls,</i>
<i>the taller people would hold it up.</i>

523
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:44,291
<i>But just a month ago,</i>

524
00:44:45,916 --> 00:44:48,250
<i>that taller man collapsed.</i>

525
00:44:49,916 --> 00:44:53,541
<i>And I realized I didn't have</i>
<i>what it takes to hold the sky up.</i>

526
00:44:57,083 --> 00:44:58,750
<i>I admit I was a bit angry.</i>

527
00:44:59,250 --> 00:45:00,416
He lied to me.

528
00:45:00,500 --> 00:45:01,875
I was seriously angry.

529
00:45:02,375 --> 00:45:04,791
Then I realized, I was angry at myself.

530
00:45:05,833 --> 00:45:09,583
How could I believe
that he'd always be here for me?

531
00:45:09,666 --> 00:45:13,125
How could I be so naive
to think that I could be

532
00:45:13,750 --> 00:45:15,625
his little girl forever?

533
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:19,458
<i>There are things,</i>

534
00:45:19,541 --> 00:45:23,666
<i>no matter how long</i>
<i>you might have prepared for it,</i>

535
00:45:23,750 --> 00:45:26,583
<i>it doesn't make you</i>
<i>any less sad when it happens.</i>

536
00:45:28,833 --> 00:45:31,125
<i>Hello? I have a question.</i>

537
00:45:31,208 --> 00:45:35,125
I heard that people stay warm
for a while after they died.

538
00:45:35,208 --> 00:45:37,791
I'm worried that he might feel cold now.

539
00:45:37,875 --> 00:45:39,541
Do you think he'd feel cold?

540
00:45:43,250 --> 00:45:46,333
I should have brought him a jacket.

541
00:45:50,833 --> 00:45:53,250
This month, I finally figured it out.

542
00:45:54,041 --> 00:45:56,916
It's fine even if I can't hold the sky up.

543
00:45:57,000 --> 00:45:58,708
It's okay because there are

544
00:45:58,791 --> 00:46:01,375
aliens.

545
00:46:02,250 --> 00:46:03,458
What the heck?

546
00:46:04,875 --> 00:46:07,458
What a lame punchline.

547
00:46:08,500 --> 00:46:10,333
This radio

548
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:13,916
was my dad's way of communicating

549
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:16,000
with the aliens.

550
00:46:16,583 --> 00:46:18,500
My dad often said that nowadays,

551
00:46:18,583 --> 00:46:20,583
people don't fix things.
They just toss them.

552
00:46:20,666 --> 00:46:24,291
Back in their days,
they fixed everything that was broken. So…

553
00:46:25,666 --> 00:46:27,666
I've fixed your radio, Dad.

554
00:46:28,958 --> 00:46:30,666
I'll keep searching for aliens.

555
00:46:30,750 --> 00:46:32,041
Go, Le-le.

556
00:46:32,125 --> 00:46:33,083
Go, Le-le.

557
00:46:33,166 --> 00:46:35,041
- Go, Le-le.
- We're here with you.

558
00:46:36,166 --> 00:46:37,583
You can do it.

559
00:46:48,208 --> 00:46:49,041
Sometimes,

560
00:46:50,458 --> 00:46:52,625
people eventually get forgotten.

561
00:46:52,708 --> 00:46:54,125
But I have to say,

562
00:46:55,416 --> 00:46:57,458
my dad was such a show-off,

563
00:46:57,541 --> 00:46:59,833
so if anyone still remembers him,

564
00:46:59,916 --> 00:47:01,833
I'm sure he'll be overjoyed.

565
00:47:06,041 --> 00:47:08,166
Perhaps by doing so,

566
00:47:08,250 --> 00:47:10,208
he can be remembered

567
00:47:10,291 --> 00:47:11,625
forever.

568
00:47:15,041 --> 00:47:15,875
Right?

569
00:47:23,625 --> 00:47:24,500
So,

570
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:26,791
what I want to say is,

571
00:47:27,291 --> 00:47:28,125
Dad,

572
00:47:28,875 --> 00:47:31,291
as long as I get to perform on stage,

573
00:47:32,208 --> 00:47:35,958
I'll keep exploiting you.

574
00:47:38,125 --> 00:47:40,500
You can't do anything about it, can you?

575
00:47:41,041 --> 00:47:42,416
What? What did you say?

576
00:47:42,958 --> 00:47:44,583
I can't hear you.

577
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:16,166
<i>It's okay if you forgot.</i>

578
00:48:17,125 --> 00:48:18,500
<i>I'll remember.</i>

579
00:48:21,166 --> 00:48:23,291
<i>As long as I keep talking about you,</i>

580
00:48:24,333 --> 00:48:25,750
<i>I believe I won't forget you.</i>

581
00:48:27,500 --> 00:48:28,375
<i>I'll keep going…</i>

582
00:48:34,291 --> 00:48:36,041
<i>until I also start forgetting.</i>

583
00:52:49,208 --> 00:52:54,208
